{"title_page": "June Almeida", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]] and  [[Thomas Henry Flewett]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]], a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> Her skills in electron microscopy earned her an international reputation.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nIn 1964, Almeida was recruited by [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]] in London.  By 1967, she had earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.) on the basis of her research and the resulting publications, while working in Canada, at Toronto's [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] and then in London at St Thomas.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1967, she continued her research at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]] (RPGMS),<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> which is now part of the [[Imperial College School of Medicine]]. \n\nShe succeeded in identifying viruses that were previously unknown, including\u2014in 1966\u2014a group of viruses that was later named [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\"/><ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} Her [[immune electron microscopy]] (IEM) innovations and insights contributed to research related to the diagnosis of [[hepatitis B]], [[HIV]], and [[rubella]], among other viral diseases. Her electron micrographs continue to be included in virology review textbooks, decades after she produced them.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Major contributions==\nIn their 2013 book entitled ''To Catch a Virus'', John Booss and Marilyn J. August describe how Almeida \"played a crucial role in adapting the electron microscope to clinical diagnostic virology work.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book|last1=Booss|first1=John|url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217|title=To Catch a Virus|last2=August|first2=Marilyn J.|publisher=ASM Press|year=2013|isbn=978-1-55581-507-3|location=Washington, DC|pages=197-249|chapter=Chapter 7: Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes|quote=ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"|authorlink=John Boos|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>{{rp|209}}<ref group=\"Notes\">In the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigens\" in John Booss and Marilyn J. August's 2013 ''To catch a virus'', they describe the how \"refinements in electron microscopy (EM)...greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\" ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"</ref>\n\nIn 1963, Almeida pioneered a technique in [[immune electron microscopy]] (IEM), to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\"/> \n\nIn the 1960s, Almeida and [[Anthony Peter Waterson]] were using [[negative staining]] for the EM of viruses\u2014a technique that was both \"rapid and simple\u2014and provided excellent detailed observations of viral morphology\", which Almeida and Waterson said, had \"revolutionized the electron microscopy of viruses\" \"overnight\".<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} In the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigens\", Booss and August describe how, prior to the 1960s work of Almeida and Waterson, very few improvements had been made on the initial 1941 \"proof of principle aggregation of virus by virus-specific antibody observable by [electron microscope (EI)].\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}}\n\nIn 1966, using her new techniques, Almeida was able to identify a group of \"previously uncharacterised human respiratory viruses\", while collaborating with [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]],<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} then director of the [[Common Cold Research Centre]]<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> in [[Salisbury]] in [[Wiltshire]].<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> Tyrrell suggested calling the new group \"coronaviruses\". The coronavirus family of viruses now includes the [[SARS virus]]<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> and the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV2]] virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} \n\nIn 1967, using the IEM aggregation method, she produced the first visualization of rubella virus.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\" /><ref name=\"Lancet_Best_1967\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(67)92302-1| issn = 0140-6736| volume = 290| issue = 7509| pages = 237\u2013239| last1 = Best| first1 = Jennifer M| last2 = Banatvala| first2 = J. E.| last3 = Almeida| first3 = June D| last4 = Waterson| first4 = A. P.| title = Morphological characteristics of rubella virus| journal = [[The Lancet]]| access-date =18 April 2020| date = 29 July 1967| url = https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(67)92302-1/abstract}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511.1\u20131511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[The BMJ]]| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = 2440895 |issn=| doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434 |bibcode = 1963Sci...142.1487A}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nIn 1947, when Almeida was 16, she left school, and in spite of her academic strength, she did not have the financial means to attend university at that time.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nBy 1964, Almeida had earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.), based on her publications of her research undertaken at the Ontario Cancer Institute and at St Thomas on electron micrographic research of antibodies.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\n==Early career==\n\nIn 1947, she began working as a [[histopathology]] technician, first, at the [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], and then at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where she worked until 1954.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nIn Toronto, Canada in 1954,  she was hired for a newly-opened position as [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] technician at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]],<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} where she worked for ten years. \n\nWhile working as an electronmicroscopist, she and her Cancer Institute colleagues produced a series of studies applying negative staining to clinical problems.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn 1963 she was the first of three authors who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| access-date = 18 April 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487\u20131489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, she co-published her research, in which she \"negatively stained aggregates of antigen...and antibody\" with the electron microscope.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1084/jem.118.3.327| issn = 0022-1007| volume = 118| issue = 3| pages = 327\u2013340| last1 = Almeida| first1 = June| last2 = Cinader| first2 = Bernhard| last3 = Howatson| first3 = Allan| title = The Structure of Antigen-Antibody Complexes: A Study by Electron Microscopy| journal = [[Journal of Experimental Medicine]] (JEM)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1 September 1963| url = https://rupress.org/jem/article/118/3/327/3553/THE-STRUCTURE-OF-ANTIGEN-ANTIBODY-COMPLEXES-A}}</ref>\n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn 1964, Tony Waterson, who had just been appointed as chair of microbiology at St Thomas, met Almeida while visiting Toronto, and recruited her to join his research team<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom\u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]], now part of [[King's College London]]. At St Thomas, Almeida worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/>\n\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|thumb|200px|Electron micrograph of \"corona\" (crown) virus produced by Almeida in 1966]]\nIn 1966, Waterson and Almeida collaborated with the physician and director of research on the common cold, David Tyrrell, who was working on a new organ culture system. Tyrrell's team had been attempting to detect the presence of [[rhinovirus]]es in tissue cultures of cells that they had produced in the lab. They wanted to detect a specific respiratory virus they called B814. The Swedish professor Bertil Hoorn could make all Tyrrell's respiratory viruses in organ cultures of cells from the human airway in the laboratory, except for virus B814. This organ culture system meant they did not have to depend on human volunteers to do research on these viruses. They wanted a reliable method to detect virus B814.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|94}} \n\nIn his 2002 co-authored book, entitled ''Cold Wars'', Tyrrell described how when he first met Almeida, she seemed to be \"extending the range of the electron microscope to new limits.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} According to Tyrrell, prior to Almeida's innovative work, it was generally accepted that viruses had to be concentrated and purified to detect them with the electron microscope. When Almeida told Tyrrell that she could \"find virus particles\" in the organ cultures that they had collected, with her \"new, improved techniques\", he was skeptical.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} Tyrrell's team sent samples to Almeida in London. These included a sample prepared with the B814 virus, along with samples infected with influenza and herpes, which were well-known. When Almeida examined the samples through her microscope grids, \"she recognized all the known viruses, and her pictures revealed their structure beautifully. But more importantly, she also saw virus particles in the B814 sample.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} She told Tyrrell that the B814 specimens had reminded her of particles she had previously studied in a \"disease called infectious bronchitis of chickens\" and in another disease\u2014\"mouse hepatitis liver inflammation.\" Her papers on these had been rejected because the referees considered her [[electron micrograph]]s to be \"bad pictures\" of known influenza virus particles. She told him she now knew that these \"three viruses were something quite new.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}\n\nAccording to Tyrrell, once Almeida had identified the \"previously unrecognised group of viruses\", they met in Waterson's office, to decide on its name. The viruses appeared to be surrounded by a \"halo\", which in Latin is \"corona\", and the \"name coronavirus\" was born.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} \n\nIn 1966, Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Postgraduate Medical School of London (RPGMS)===\n\nThree years later, in 1967, when Waterson took a position at the Royal Postgraduate Medical School (RPGMS), she also moved to begin work there. \n\nIn 1968, she co-published an article in ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', on \"avian infectious bronchitis virus\".<ref name=\"JGV_Berry_Almeida_1968\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97| issn = 0022-1317| volume = 3| issue = 1| pages = 97\u2013102| last1 = Berry| first1 = D. M.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = June D.| title = The Morphological and Biological Effects of Various Antisera on Avian Infectious Bronchitis Virus| journal = [[Journal of General Virology]] (JGV)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1968| url = https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/jgv/10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, using her immune electronmicroscopy technique, she made the landmark discovery that the [[hepatitis B]] virus had \"two immunologically distinct components\"\u2014an \"outer coat and a small inner component\".<ref name=\"Nahmias_2012\">{{Cite book| publisher = Springer Science & Business Media| isbn = 978-1-4684-1012-9| last1 = Nahmias| first1 = Andr\u00e9 J.| last2 = O'Reilly| first2 = Richard J.| title = Immunology of Human Infection: Part II: Viruses and Parasites; Immunodiagnosis and Prevention of Infectious Diseases| date = 2012-12-06}}</ref>\n\n===Wellcome Institute===\nShe spent her final years of her professional career at the [[Wellcome Institute]] before she retired.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\">{{cite ODNB |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |date= January 2011 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/99332 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref>  While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n==Influences== \nAccording to a 7 March article in the ''[[Herald Scotland]],'' [[Hugh Pennington]] said that Almeida was his mentor.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\nAt the Royal Postgraduate Medical School (RPGMS), in 1970, Almeida taught [[Albert Kapikian]] the technique of immune electron microscopy (IEM). Kapikian, who was visiting for six months from the United States [[National Institutes of Health]]\u2014 used her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]], now known as the Norovirus.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/><ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nDuring the early months of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese scientists credited her work\u2014including techniques she developed\u2014with the early identification of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], according to Pennington.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped produce micrographs of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979 |last=Almeida |first=June D.}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nA 15 April 2020 ''BBC Scotland News'' said that Almedia was \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst |work=BBC Scotland News |date=15 April 2020 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Group of coronavirus ==\nIn a 7 March 2020 interview with the ''Herald'', Pennington spoke of Almeida's research had informed with work of Chinese researchers during the pandemic.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], the little known story was first published by the ''Herald'' in Scotland on 7 March, the [[BBC]] on 15 April,<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> the ''[[National Geographic]]'' on April 17.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]] |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce. \n\nHer daughter Joyce, a psychiatrist, has two daughters.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nHer first marriage ended in divorce in 1982. \n\nShe retired in 1985 to [[Bexhill-on-Sea]] with her second husband, Phillip Samuel Gardner, a virologist.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nIn the late 1980s, she co-published \"negative staining electron micrographs\" of [[HIV]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>  \n\nAlmeida died in Bexhill from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{reflist|group=\"Publications\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]] and  [[Thomas Henry Flewett]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]], a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> Her skills in electron microscopy earned her an international reputation.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nIn 1964, Almeida was recruited by [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]] in London.  By 1967, she had earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.) on the basis of her research and the resulting publications, while working in Canada, at Toronto's [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] and then in London at St Thomas.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1967, she continued her research at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]] (RPGMS),<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> which is now part of the [[Imperial College School of Medicine]]. \n\nShe succeeded in identifying viruses that were previously unknown, including\u2014in 1966\u2014a group of viruses that was later named [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\"/><ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} Her [[immune electron microscopy]] (IEM) innovations and insights contributed to research related to the diagnosis of [[hepatitis B]], [[HIV]], and [[rubella]], among other viral diseases. Her electron micrographs continue to be included in virology review textbooks, decades after she produced them.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Major contributions==\nIn their 2013 book entitled ''To Catch a Virus'', John Booss and Marilyn J. August describe how Almeida \"played a crucial role in adapting the electron microscope to clinical diagnostic virology work.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book|last1=Booss|first1=John|url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217|title=To Catch a Virus|last2=August|first2=Marilyn J.|publisher=ASM Press|year=2013|isbn=978-1-55581-507-3|location=Washington, DC|pages=197-249|chapter=Chapter 7: Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes|quote=ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"|authorlink=John Boos|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>{{rp|209}}<ref group=\"Notes\">In the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigens\" in John Booss and Marilyn J. August's 2013 ''To catch a virus'', they describe the how \"refinements in electron microscopy (EM)...greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\" ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"</ref>\n\nIn 1963, Almeida pioneered a technique in [[immune electron microscopy]] (IEM), to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\"/> \n\nIn the 1960s, Almeida and [[Anthony Peter Waterson]] were using [[negative staining]] for the EM of viruses\u2014a technique that was both \"rapid and simple\u2014and provided excellent detailed observations of viral morphology\", which Almeida and Waterson said, had \"revolutionized the electron microscopy of viruses\" \"overnight\".<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} In the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigens\", Booss and August describe how, prior to the 1960s work of Almeida and Waterson, very few improvements had been made on the initial 1941 \"proof of principle aggregation of virus by virus-specific antibody observable by [electron microscope (EI)].\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}}\n\nIn 1966, using her new techniques, Almeida was able to identify a group of \"previously uncharacterised human respiratory viruses\", while collaborating with [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]],<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} then director of the [[Common Cold Research Centre]]<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> in [[Salisbury]] in [[Wiltshire]].<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> Tyrrell suggested calling the new group \"coronaviruses\". The coronavirus family of viruses now includes the [[SARS virus]]<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> and the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV2]] virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} \n\nIn 1967, using the IEM aggregation method, she produced the first visualization of rubella virus.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\" /><ref name=\"Lancet_Best_1967\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(67)92302-1| issn = 0140-6736| volume = 290| issue = 7509| pages = 237\u2013239| last1 = Best| first1 = Jennifer M| last2 = Banatvala| first2 = J. E.| last3 = Almeida| first3 = June D| last4 = Waterson| first4 = A. P.| title = Morphological characteristics of rubella virus| journal = [[The Lancet]]| access-date =18 April 2020| date = 29 July 1967| url = https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(67)92302-1/abstract}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511.1\u20131511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[The BMJ]]| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = 2440895 |issn=| doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434 |bibcode = 1963Sci...142.1487A}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nIn 1947, when Almeida was 16, she left school, and in spite of her academic strength, she did not have the financial means to attend university at that time.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nBy 1964, Almeida had earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.), based on her publications of her research undertaken at the Ontario Cancer Institute and at St Thomas on electron micrographic research of antibodies.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\n==Early career==\n\nIn 1947, she began working as a [[histopathology]] technician, first, at the [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], and then at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where she worked until 1954.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nIn Toronto, Canada in 1954,  she was hired for a newly-opened position as [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] technician at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]],<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} where she worked for ten years. \n\nWhile working as an electronmicroscopist, she and her Cancer Institute colleagues \"produced a series of studies applying negative staining to clinical problems.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn 1963 she was the first  of three authors, who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| access-date = 18 April 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487\u20131489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, she co-published her research in which she \"negatively stained aggregates of antigen...and antibody\" with the electron microscope.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1084/jem.118.3.327| issn = 0022-1007| volume = 118| issue = 3| pages = 327\u2013340| last1 = Almeida| first1 = June| last2 = Cinader| first2 = Bernhard| last3 = Howatson| first3 = Allan| title = The Structure of Antigen-Antibody Complexes: A Study by Electron Microscopy| journal = [[Journal of Experimental Medicine]] (JEM)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1 September 1963| url = https://rupress.org/jem/article/118/3/327/3553/THE-STRUCTURE-OF-ANTIGEN-ANTIBODY-COMPLEXES-A}}</ref>\n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn 1964, Tony Waterson, who had just been appointed as chair of microbiology at St Thomas, met Almeida while visiting Toronto, and recruited her to join his research team,<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom, \u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]\u2014now part of [[King's College London]]. At St Thomas, Almeida worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/> \n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|thumb|left|200px|Electron micrograph of 'corona' (crown) virus produced by Almeida in 1966]]\nIn 1966, Waterson and Almeida collaborated with the physician and director of research on the common cold, David Tyrrell, who was working on a new organ culture system. Tyrrell's team had been attempting to detect the presence of [[rhinovirus]]es in tissue cultures of cells that they had produced in the lab. They wanted to detect a specific respiratory virus they called B814. A Swedish professor, Bertil Hoorn could make all Tyrrell's respiratory viruses in organ cultures of cells from the human airway in the laboratory, except for virus B814. This organ culture system meant they did not have to depend on human volunteers to do research on these viruses. They wanted a reliable method to detect virus B814.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|94}} \n\nIn his 2002 co-authored book, entitled, ''Cold wars'', Tyrrell described how when he first met Almeida, she seemed to be \"extending the range of the electron microscope to new limits.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} According to Tyrrell, prior to Almeida's innovative work, it was generally accepted that viruses had to be concentrated and purified to detect them with the electron microscope. When Almeida told Tyrrell that she could \"find virus particles\" in the organ cultures that they had collected, with her \"new, improved techniques\", he was skeptical.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} Tyrrell's team sent samples to Almeida in London. These included a sample prepared with the B814 virus, along with samples infected with influenza and herpes, which were well-known. When Almeida examined the samples through her microscope grids, \"she recognized all the known viruses, and her pictures revealed their structure beautifully. But more importantly, she also saw virus particles in the B814 sample.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} She told Tyrrell that the B814 specimens had reminded her of particles she had previously studied in a \"disease called infectious bronchitis of chickens\" and in another disease- \"mouse hepatitis liver inflammation.\" Her papers on these had been rejected because the referees considered her [[electron micrograph]]s to be \"bad pictures\" of known influenza virus particles. She told him she now knew that these \"three viruses were something quite new.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}\n\nAccording to Tyrrell, once Almeida had identified the \"previously unrecognised group of viruses\", they met in Waterson's office, to decide on its name. The viruses appeared to be surrounded by a \"halo\", which in Latin is \"corona\"\u2014the \"name coronavirus\" was born.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} \n\nIn 1966, Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Postgraduate Medical School of London (RPGMS)===\n\nThree years later, in 1967, when Waterson took a position at the Royal Postgraduate Medical School (RPGMS), she also moved to begin work there. \n\nIn 1968, she co-published an article in ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', on \"avian infectious bronchitis virus\".<ref name=\"JGV_Berry_Almeida_1968\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97| issn = 0022-1317| volume = 3| issue = 1| pages = 97\u2013102| last1 = Berry| first1 = D. M.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = June D.| title = The Morphological and Biological Effects of Various Antisera on Avian Infectious Bronchitis Virus| journal = [[Journal of General Virology]] (JGV)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1968| url = https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/jgv/10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, using her immune electronmicroscopy technique, she made the landmark discovery that the [[hepatitis B]] virus had \"two immunologically distinct components\"\u2014an \"outer coat and a small inner component\".<ref name=\"Nahmias_2012\">{{Cite book| publisher = Springer Science & Business Media| isbn = 978-1-4684-1012-9| last1 = Nahmias| first1 = Andr\u00e9 J.| last2 = O'Reilly| first2 = Richard J.| title = Immunology of Human Infection: Part II: Viruses and Parasites; Immunodiagnosis and Prevention of Infectious Diseases| date = 2012-12-06}}</ref>\n\n===Wellcome Institute===\nShe spent her final years of her professional career at the [[Wellcome Institute]] before she retired.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\">{{cite ODNB |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |date= January 2011 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/99332 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref>  While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Influences== \nAccording to a 7 March article in the ''[[Herald Scotland]],'' [[Hugh Pennington]] said that Almeida was his mentor.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\nAt the Royal Postgraduate Medical School (RPGMS), in 1970, Almeida taught [[Albert Kapikian]] the technique of immune electron microscopy (IEM). Kapikian, who was visiting for six months from the United States [[National Institutes of Health]]\u2014 used her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]], now known as the Norovirus.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/><ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nDuring the early months of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese scientists credited her work\u2014including techniques she developed\u2014with the early identification of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], according to Pennington.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped produce micrographs of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979 |last=Almeida |first=June D.}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nA 15 April 2020 ''BBC Scotland News'' said that Almedia was \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst |work=BBC Scotland News |date=15 April 2020 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Group of coronavirus ==\nIn a 7 March 2020 interview with the ''Herald'', Pennington spoke of Almeida's research had informed with work of Chinese researchers during the pandemic.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], the little known story was first published by the ''Herald'' in Scotland on 7 March, the [[BBC]] on 15 April,<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> the ''[[National Geographic]]'' on April 17.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]] |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce. \n\nHer daughter Joyce, a psychiatrist, has two daughters.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nHer first marriage ended in divorce in 1982. \n\nShe retired in 1985 to [[Bexhill-on-Sea]] with her second husband, Phillip Samuel Gardner, a virologist.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> \n\nIn the late 1980s, she co-published \"negative staining electron micrographs\" of [[HIV]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>  \n\nAlmeida died in Bexhill from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=\"ODNB_Banatvala_2011_01\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{reflist|group=\"Publications\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "name_user": "Amire80", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor copyrediting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_Almeida"}
{"title_page": "Jory Nash", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Jory Nash\n| image =\n| caption =Jory Nash\n| image_size = 200px\n| birth_name = Jory Kevin Nash\n| background = solo_singer\n| instrument = [[Vocals]], [[guitar]]\n| genre = [[Independent music|Indie]], [[Folk music|folk]]\n| occupation = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active = N/A - present\n| label =[[Thin Man Records]]\n| website = [http://www.jorynash.com/ www.jorynash.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jory Nash''' is a [[folk music]]-oriented [[Canadian]] [[singer-songwriter]] and musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jory-nash-p482164/biography|title=Jory Nash|last=MacNeil|first=Jason|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nJory Nash blends elements of folk, jazz, blues, soul and pop into an original stew of sound. He plays primarily acoustic guitar and piano, and occasionally plays the 5 string banjo.\n\nJory Nash is based in Toronto, Ontario, Canada and tours regularly.\n\n==Albums==\n* ''One Way Down'' (1998)\n* ''Tangle With the Ghost'' (2000)\n* ''Lo-Fi Northern Blues'' (2002)\n* ''Spaz Loves Weezie'' (2004)\n* ''Folk, Jazz, Blues & Soul'' (2007)\n* ''New Blue Day'' (2009)\n* ''Little Pilgrim'' (2012)\n* ''The Many Hats of Jory Nash'' (2015)\n* ''Wilderness Years'' (2018)\n\n==Awards==\n\n2001 Ontario Council of Folk Festivals \"Songs From The Heart\" Award for the song \"When I Walk Out\"\n\n2010 Penguin Eggs Magazine's Critic's Poll Album of the Year for \"New Blue Day\"\n\n2010 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Producer for \"New Blue Day\"\n\n2013 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Producer for \"Little Pilgrim\"\n\n2015 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Contemporary Singer & Best Producer for \"The Many Hats of Jory Nash\"\n\n==Career Outside of Music==\nJory Nash is a director at the Canadian company \"ALIVE Outdoors\" an experiential and outdoor education company specializing in the creation and delivery of customized, meaningful programs for schools and organizations. He works with many students in the Canadian Wilderness to provide an outdoor education and camp experience.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jorynash.com Official site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nash, Jory}}\n[[Category:Canadian folk singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-singer-stub}}\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Jory Nash\n| image =\n| caption =Jory Nash\n| image_size = 200px\n| birth_name = Jory Kevin Nash\n| background = solo_singer\n| instrument = [[Vocals]], [[guitar]]\n| genre = [[Independent music|Indie]], [[Folk music|folk]]\n| occupation = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active = N/A - present\n| label =[[Thin Man Records]]\n| website = [http://www.jorynash.com/ www.jorynash.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jory Nash''' is a [[folk music]]-oriented [[Canadian]] [[singer-songwriter]] and musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jory-nash-p482164/biography|title=Jory Nash|last=MacNeil|first=Jason|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nJory Nash blends elements of folk, jazz, blues, soul and pop into an original stew of sound. He plays primarily acoustic guitar and piano, and occasionally plays the 5 string banjo.\n\nJory Nash is based in Toronto, Ontario, Canada and tours regularly.\n\n==Albums==\n* ''One Way Down'' (1998)\n* ''Tangle With the Ghost'' (2000)\n* ''Lo-Fi Northern Blues'' (2002)\n* ''Spaz Loves Weezie'' (2004)\n* ''Folk, Jazz, Blues & Soul'' (2007)\n* ''New Blue Day'' (2009)\n* ''Little Pilgrim'' (2012)\n* ''The Many Hats of Jory Nash'' (2015)\n* ''Wilderness Years'' (2018)\n\n==Awards==\n\n2001 Ontario Council of Folk Festivals \"Songs From The Heart\" Award for the song \"When I Walk Out\"\n\n2010 Penguin Eggs Magazine's Critic's Poll Album of the Year for \"New Blue Day\"\n\n2010 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Producer for \"New Blue Day\"\n\n2013 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Producer for \"Little Pilgrim\"\n\n2015 Canadian Folk Music Awards Nominee for Best Contemporary Singer & Best Producer for \"The Many Hats of Jory Nash\"\n\n==Career Outside of Music==\nJory Nash is a director at the Canadian company \"ALIVE Outdoors\" an experiential and outdoor education company specializing in the creation and delivery of customized, meaningful programs for schools and organizations. He works with many students in the Canadian Wilderness to provide an outdoor education and camp experience.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jorynash.com Official site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nash, Jory}}\n[[Category:Canadian folk singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-singer-stub}}\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hatchens", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jory_Nash"}
